                <head>244. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On July 26, the Egyptian Government nationalized the Suez Canal Company,
                    precipitating an international crisis. The U.S.–U.K. “special relationship” came
                    under considerable stress in the succeeding months as a result of a divergence
                    of views at various stages of the crisis and particularly by the British
                    decisions to refer the Suez Canal dispute to the United Nations Security Council
                    and to participate with France in hostilities against Egypt without informing
                    the United States Government. For extensive documentation on the crisis, see
                    volume XVI.</p>
            </div>
